Observation Details: Definitely 3 Anhingas.  Clear looks at plumage and structure through bins. Head/neck long and thin with needle-like bill at a distance. Narrow, pointed wings with a longer and more wedged tail than DCCO. Silvery-gray feathers on upper parts were visible when angled favorably toward me. Two adult M, 1 F (or immature?). They were kettling with a TUVU and circled the same area for several minutes before gliding out of sight to the north east. I saw two yesterday, also in flight, over NN Park, which is quite close to the middle school (and roughly in a NE direction). One has to wonder if these aren't the same two from yesterday, with a new addition. Unfortunately I only had bins, no camera, but I have cell phone video available. A lovely lunch break surprise.
Third time this month I’ve encountered Anhinga in NN. Two female/immature. Perched on fallen trees in the lake directly in front of Pine Tree Overlook.

Photos. Flew over my head from behind while on the bridge spanning the lake; I was  facing the concrete pipe. They circled several times, soaring over the trees and then headed  southwest. M and F. Long, pointed wings; long sightly wedged tail; long neck with long spear-like bill. Silver-gray feathers clearly visible.

Observation Details: A very soft, low cooing emanated from the edge of the marsh, just next to the road/parking area at the end of Maryus Rd. I heard the sound for two extended periods (5+ minutes each), once upon exiting my vehicle and again before leaving. The bird vocalized every 2-3 seconds and never seemed further than 10 feet away, and often closer. When I would approach the marsh edge, the sound would stop momentarily and resume again 5-10 feet away. It never flushed, however. Nor was I able to visually detect it, despite considerable effort. It is remarkable to me that it evaded my sight at that proximity. Neither phone nor camera were able to pick up the sound over the wind.

Heard immediately upon exiting vehicle from edge of parking lot, to the right of visitor center/bathrooms just before the walkway to the NW facing marsh overlook platform. Both birds audible concurrently, about 50 feet apart.

At the time I did not know what kind they were, but upon listening to various recordings of likely species it became clear that these were Striped Owls. Their high, thin, wheezing sound is very distinctive.

Continuing. Seen flying at a height of about 150 ft. Large round head, facial disk. Stouter body, shorter tail than harrier. Unable to get photo as the bird flew directly into sunlight after which point it was too far away to shoot. Flying the same direction at about the same height as the bird I believed to be a SEOW last Sunday, but was unable to confirm owing to low light and a brief glimpse.

Observation Details: Female. Seen from directly across the river, perched on the lower surface of the canyon, about 3m above water. Long, thick bill. Uniformly dark upperparts, much darker than the blue of a Ringed or Belted Kingfisher. Mostly white underparts except for band across chest. Considerably smaller in size than other north american kingfishers (my first reaction, before looking through bins, wast to assume it was a Black Phoebe).

Both birds flew off as I tried to cross furtively under the tree they were slowly moving around in, in an effort to get inside and grab my camera. The birds also appeared bulkier in flight than what I associate with HOFI.

Observation Details: While running I observed a small dark bird in a gravel driveway, drinking from a puddle, about 8-10 feet from the road. When seen initially with peripheral vision I assumed it was a blackbird or grackle given the behavior on the ground and the general dark appearance. I quickly realized that the shape and size were way off so I stopped running to examine more closely. When I came even with the driveway I realized it was not black but was decidedly dark blue, rather uniformly, though slightly darker on back with wings closed.The individual had a heavy black bill. Bird was in shadow, so colors were not particularly pronounced, but the reddish-brown wingbars were visible, particularly when the bird flew another 10 feet back into a bush. At that point I lost sight and continued my run.
